.SH NAME
Element.scrollLeft \- Element: scrollLeft property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Element.scrollLeft\f[B]\f[R] property gets or sets the
number of pixels that an element\[cq]s content is scrolled from its left
edge.
.PP
If the element\[cq]s \f[CR]direction\f[R] is \f[CR]rtl\f[R]
(right\-to\-left), then \f[CR]scrollLeft\f[R] is \f[CR]0\f[R] when the
scrollbar is at its rightmost position (at the start of the scrolled
content), and then increasingly negative as you scroll towards the end
of the content.
.PP
It can be specified as any integer value.
However:
.IP \[bu] 2
If the element can\[cq]t be scrolled (e.g., it has no overflow),
\f[CR]scrollLeft\f[R] is set to \f[CR]0\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
If specified as a value less than \f[CR]0\f[R] (greater than
\f[CR]0\f[R] for right\-to\-left elements), \f[CR]scrollLeft\f[R] is set
to \f[CR]0\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
If specified as a value greater than the maximum that the content can be
scrolled, \f[CR]scrollLeft\f[R] is set to the maximum.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] On systems using display scaling,
\f[CR]scrollLeft\f[R] may give you a decimal value.
.RE
.SH VALUE
A number.
.SH EXAMPLES
